hands_on_practices.solution:
Near equilibrium and at fixed temperature, linear irreversible thermodynamics writes each flux as a linear combination of all admissible thermodynamic forces. With the choices specified in the statement, take the diffusive force to be $X_{m}=-\nabla c$ and the electric force to be $X_{e}=\vec{E}$. Then the most general linear constitutive relations are
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
\vec{J}_{m} \\
\vec{J}_{e}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
L_{mm} & L_{me} \\
L_{em} & L_{ee}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
X_{m} \\
X_{e}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
L_{mm} & L_{me} \\
L_{em} & L_{ee}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
-\nabla c \\
\vec{E}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
The observation that an electric field drives a steady solute mass flux means the cross-coefficient $L_{me}$ is nonzero, i.e.,
$$
\vec{J}_{m}=\dots+L_{me}\,\vec{E}.
$$
By Onsagerâ€™s reciprocal relations (microscopic reversibility, no magnetic field or Coriolis effects), the cross-coefficients are symmetric:
$$
L_{me}=L_{em}.
$$
Therefore $L_{em}\neq 0$, and the reciprocal coupled effect is that the diffusive force $X_{m}=-\nabla c$ drives the conjugate flux $\vec{J}_{e}$:
$$
\vec{J}_{e}=\dots+L_{em}\,(-\nabla c).
$$
Thus, a concentration gradient of the solute produces an electric current density. This corresponds to option B. Options A and C misuse the roles of forces and fluxes; D is false because neutral but polarizable solutes can couple to $\vec{E}$ via cross effects; E contradicts steady-state transport where viscous drag balances driving forces.
